As shown in Fig. S6, the FL intensity of system gradually decreases with the increase of PP concentration up to 100 μmol/L. Also, pH and incubation time was studied for enzyme reaction. From Figs. S7 and S8, it could be found that PP can be hydrolyzed to the greatest extent by ALP with pH 8.2 and 30 min reaction time. Based on the above optimal conditions, the fluorescence spectra of APBA-Au NCs/PP/TYR system with different concentration of ALP were recorded in Fig. 4
                        A. There are two good linear relationships (R2>0.99) between the fluorescence intensity ratio F/F0 and the ALP concentration. As shown in Fig. 4B, the regression equation are F/F0 = 1.0003–1.7637CALP, U/L (R2 = 0.9948) in the range of 0.02–0.1 U/L, and F/F0 = 0.8355–0.1397CALP, U/L (R2 = 0.9999) in the range of 0.1–2.0 U/L. The detection limit of ALP is 0.005 U/L. We also compared this method with other reported ﬂuorescent methods for ALP detection in linear range and detection limit (Table 1
                        ). It is found that the detection limit of proposed method was much lower than that of most previously reported methods. In previously studies, the majority of sensing approaches have been construct relied on the discrimination of pyrophosphate and phosphate by Cu2+ [40,41] and strong binding affinity between Ce3+ and phosphate [42,43]. Under the alkaline condition, copper ions are easily converted into copper hydroxide precipitates. And, Ce, as a kind of rare earth elements, is relatively expensive. Furthermore, several fluorescent probes containing phosphoric acid group with lower FL intensity have been designed and developed [44–46]. After hydrolyzation by ALP, the products exhibit high fluorescence signal. Although this “turn-on” sensing modes are easy to operate, several disadvantages of the mentioned methods still exist, such as the complicated synthesis processes and lack of sensitivity for single enzyme reaction. Compared with the previous method, bi-enzyme amplification sensing system accompanied with specific identification of boric acid has greatly improved the sensitivity. More important, biologically friendly substances, no metal ions and rare earth elements, make our work to be a more favorable candidate for the following in vivo imaging experiment.
